First question, based on data hosted on an external website.

Lets again go back to the pulse rate data that we used previously. The data was supplied by Dr Richard J. Wilson, Department of Mathematics, University of Queensland. The following is the link for the data and the metadata: see here. Read the description and understand which variable means what.

When you try to practice at home, copy and run the following two lines first. This creates a dataframe called \(\texttt{pulse_data}\) that has the data from the above link.

pulse_data = read.table(url("http://www.statsci.org/data/oz/ms212.txt"), header = TRUE)
pulse_data = pulse_data[complete.cases(pulse_data), ]



(Question 1): Covariance and Correlation


A. We are going to build a regression model today using the pulse measurement before the experiment as the independent variable or covariate and the pulse measurement after the experiment as the dependent variable or response. From the metadata, can you guess what columns I need to use here? Also, following usual class notations, which one is \(x\), which one is \(y\) in my regression model?

Answer:

  • From the description file, the variable pulse measurement before the experiment is in the column Pulse1. Pulse measurement after the experiment is in the column Pulse2.

  • The independent variable (\(x\)) is: Pulse1.

  • The dependent variable (\(y\)) is: Pulse2.


B. Draw a scatterplot between the above two variables (i.e., pulse measurements before and after excercize). From the scatterplot, what kind of relationship do you guess here between the variables?

Answer: 

Pulse1 = pulse_data$Pulse1
Pulse2 = pulse_data$Pulse2

plot(Pulse1, Pulse2)

It seems that there is a weak increasing relationship, i.e., \(y\) is increasing with \(x\) increasing.


C. What is the covariance and correlation between the two variables? What kind of relationship do you guess here between the variables?

Answer: 

cov(Pulse1, Pulse2) # This is Covariance
## [1] 151.742
cor(Pulse1, Pulse2) # This is Correlation
## [1] 0.3614805


D. Using the same two variables, can you demonstrate that the correlation between \(\mathbf{x}\) and \(\mathbf{y}\) is the same as the correlation between correlation between \(\mathbf{y}\) and \(\mathbf{x}\) \(\big(\)i.e., cor(\(\mathbf{y, x}\)) = cor(\(\mathbf{x, y}\)) \(\big)\)?

Answer: 

# Just swapping the two variables. Check that this number is the same as the correlation before.
cor(Pulse2, Pulse1)   
## [1] 0.3614805


E. What is the Spearmans rank correlation coefficient between the two variables?

Answer: 

# Same code as correlation, but you need to add method = "spearman"
cor(Pulse1, Pulse2, method = "spearman")     
## [1] 0.4572993



(Question 2): Regression Model


A. Build the above simple linear regression model in \(\texttt{R}\). Provide the estimated regression equation.

Answer: 

# Remember, the code is <model_name> = lm( <y_variable> ~ <x_variable>, data  = <data_name>)
model = lm(Pulse2   ~ Pulse1, data = pulse_data )
model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Pulse2 ~ Pulse1, data = pulse_data)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       Pulse1  
##     31.8476       0.8581

So, my regression equation is: \(\widehat{y} = 31.85 + 0.86 x\).


B. What is the interpretation of your estimated \(\widehat{\beta}_0\)?

Answer: \(\widehat{\beta}_0 = 31.85\) is the estimated value of Pulse2 (or \(y\)) when Pulse1 (or \(x\)) is equal to 0.


C. What is the interpretation of your estimated \(\widehat{\beta}_1\)?

Answer: \(\widehat{\beta}_1 = 0.86\) is the estimated change in Pulse2 (or \(y\)) when Pulse1 (or \(x\)) changes by 1 unit.


D. Find and interpret \(R^2\), also denoted by the coefficient of determination.

Answer:

For this question, you will need the summary of the model. So lets print it first.

summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Pulse2 ~ Pulse1, data = pulse_data)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -29.09 -23.07 -17.92  28.08  72.65 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  31.8476    16.4415   1.937 0.055379 .  
## Pulse1        0.8581     0.2140   4.010 0.000113 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 29.57 on 107 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1307, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1225 
## F-statistic: 16.08 on 1 and 107 DF,  p-value: 0.0001125

Now you have to remember that the value of \(R^2\) is written beside \(\texttt{## Multiple R-squared:}.\) So, from the output table, \(R^2 = 0.1307\).

Also, \(R^2\) is the percentage of the explained variability of \(y\) by the model. So, here, only \(13\%\) variability in Pulse2 (\(y\)) is being explained by the model.


E. Verify that \(R^2\) is square of the corrleation coefficient between the two variables.

Answer: 

# Take a square of the correlation coefficient you calculated in 1C
# See that this number is same as the R^2
cor(Pulse1, Pulse2)^2
## [1] 0.1306681


F. Plot the regression line on top of the scatter plot of the data.

Answer:

For this, first do the scatterplot. Then, use the command \(\texttt{abline(<model_name>}\). You can give it a color by adding \(\texttt{col=...}\).

plot(Pulse1, Pulse2) #Scatterplot from 1B
abline(model, col="red") # Plotting the model



(Question 3) Prediction and Residuals


A. Use the model to predict the second pulse rate when the first pulse rate is 70.

Answer:

Careful! This one is tricky. The usual syntax of the code is:

predict(<model_name>, newdata = data.frame(<x_variable> = <value>))

Here the \(\texttt{<model_name>}\) is \(\texttt{model}\); \(\texttt{<x_variable>}\) is \(\texttt{Pulse1}\); \(\texttt{<value>}\) is \(\texttt{70}\). Lets complete the code now.

# Code
predict(model, newdata = data.frame(Pulse1 = 70) )
##        1 
## 91.91703


B. Use the model to predict the second pulse rate when the first pulse rate is 45.

Following the same syntax as before.

predict(model, newdata = data.frame(Pulse1 = 45))
##        1 
## 70.46366


B. Use the model to predict the second pulse rate when the first pulse rate is equal to its mean (\(\bar{x}\)). Verify that it is equal to \(\bar{y}\).

Answer: 

# Code


C. What is the estimated error standard deviation? What is the estimated error variance?

Answer:

\(\hat{\sigma} = 29.57\). \(\hat{\sigma}^2 = 874.38\).

29.57^2
## [1] 874.3849


D. Plot the residuals from the model and plot them against the fitted values. Is there any pattern?

Answer: 

plot(model, which = 1)



(Question 4): Hypothesis testing

A. Test whether the slope (\(\beta_1\)) of the regression line is significantly different from zero. Use a significance level of 0.05. State the null and alternative hypotheses, and report the p-value and your conclusion.

Answer:

\(H_0\): \(\beta_1 = 0\) vs \(H_A\): \(\beta_1 \neq 0\).

#p value = 0

p-value = 0 < 0.05. Reject \(H_0\).

B. In the above test, what is the value of the test statistic? Show that the test statistic is equal to \(\frac{\widehat{\beta}_1 \text{ - } 0}{\text{sd}(\widehat{\beta}_1)}\)?

Answer: 

0.8581/0.2140
## [1] 4.009813

C. Find the 95% confidence interval for the slope \(\beta_1\).

confint(model, level = 0.95)
##                  2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) -0.7457000 64.440900
## Pulse1       0.4339459  1.282324

D. Test whether the model makes any sense or not. Use a significance level of 0.05. State the null and alternative hypotheses, and report the p-value and your conclusion.

\(H_0\): \(\beta_1 = 0\) vs \(H_A\): \(\beta_1 \neq 0\).

p-value = 0. Reject \(H_0\).

plot(hatvalues(model), type = 'h')
